'''Fiston Kalala Mayele''' (born 24 June 1994)<ref>{{Cite web |last=Philémon |date=2022-09-23 |title=DR Congo: Filston Mayele conquering Tanzanian football |url=https://sportnewsafrica.com/en/all-african-countries/dr-congo-filston-mayele-conquering-tanzanian-football/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=Sport News Africa |language=en-US}}</ref> is a Congolese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Egyptian Premier League]] club [[Pyramids FC]] and the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]].<ref name=Soccerway>{{Cite web |title=Congo DR - F. Mayele - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway |url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/fiston-kalala-mayele/645192/ |access-date=2023-04-01 |website=us.soccerway.com}}</ref>

== Club career ==

=== Early career ===
Aged 11, Mayele began playing youth football for Young Leader during the 2008–09 season.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=ipanga |date=2017-04-17 |title=PORTRAIT : Fiston Mayele Kalala : Un buteur né ! |url=https://footrdc.com/a-la-une/portrait-fiston-mayele-kalala-buteur-ne/ |access-date=2026-05-31 |website=Foot RDC |language=fr-FR}}</ref> After a one-year break due to injury,<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Carréfoot |date=2023-07-06 |title=FISTON MAYELE, UNE ÉTOILE DESTINÉE À FAIRE BRILLER LE FOOTBALL CONGOLAIS ! |url=https://carrefoot.com/fiston-mayele/ |access-date=2026-05-31 |website=Carrefoot |language=fr-FR}}</ref> Mayele moved to [[Lubumbashi]]-based [[FC Tshakwiz]], scoring 17 goals in the third division.<ref name=":0" /> In 2015, Mayele joined {{Interlanguage link|JS Likasi|fr|Jeunesse sportive de Likasi}}, where he finished the 2015–16 season with 10 goals and seven assists.<ref name=":0" /> The following season he scored 24 goals in the local championship.<ref name=":1" />

After a one season at [[AS Simba]], Mayele moved to [[AS Vita Club]] in the Congolese [[Linafoot]] league in 2018.<ref name=":1" /> In the [[2020–21 Linafoot|2020–21 season]], he finished as runner-up on the Linafoot top scorers list.{{Citation needed|date=May 2026}}

=== Young Africans ===
On August 1, 2021, he signed a two-year deal with Tanzanian club [[Young Africans S.C.|Young Africans]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ajira |first=Wasomi |date=2022-04-03 |title=CV ya Fiston Mayele wa Yanga {{!}} Player Profile |url=https://wasomiajira.com/cv-ya-fiston-mayele-wa-yanga-player-profile/03/04/2022/ |access-date=2023-04-01 |website=Wasomi Ajira |language=en-US |archive-date=1 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230401004451/https://wasomiajira.com/cv-ya-fiston-mayele-wa-yanga-player-profile/03/04/2022/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=ajiraforum |date=2022-07-12 |title=CV ya Fiston Mayele wa Yanga {{!}}Fiston mayele salary {{!}}Mkataba wa mayele yanga |url=https://ajiraforum.com/cv-ya-fiston-mayele-wa-yanga-fiston-mayele-salary-mkataba-wa-mayele-yanga/ |access-date=2023-04-01 |website=Ajiraforum -Your Dream Job Destination{{!}} Nafasi za kazi zilizotangazwa leo |language=en-GB |archive-date=1 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230401004452/https://ajiraforum.com/cv-ya-fiston-mayele-wa-yanga-fiston-mayele-salary-mkataba-wa-mayele-yanga/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> He quickly became a fan favorite at Young Africans after scoring the decisive goal in his debut match—a Charity Shield clash against arch-rivals [[Simba SC]]—played in front of a full-capacity crowd of 60,000 at [[Benjamin Mkapa National Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Olsson |first=Andrew |date=2021-05-25 |title=Linafoot D1 : Fiston Mayele guide Vita Club vers le titre devant Sanga Balende |url=https://panafricafootball.com/linafoot-d1-fiston-mayele-guide-vita-club-vers-le-titre-devant-sanga-balende/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=Pan-Africa Football |language=en-US |archive-date=2023-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230604142533/https://panafricafootball.com/linafoot-d1-fiston-mayele-guide-vita-club-vers-le-titre-devant-sanga-balende/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=yavgrace |date=2021-05-24 |title=Linafoot D1 : Fiston Mayele guide Vita Club vers le titre devant Sanga Balende |url=https://footrdc.com/rd-congo/linafoot-d1-fiston-mayele-guide-vita-club-vers-le-titre-devant-sanga-balende/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=Foot RDC |language=fr-FR}}</ref>

During his time with Young Africans, Mayele delivered outstanding performances, scoring 12 goals in seven matches at one point, including a run of seven goals in six games.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gumbi |first=Sibongiseni |date=2022-11-30 |title=Six strikers linked with Kaizer Chiefs, are they good enough? |url=https://www.citizen.co.za/sport/soccer/local-soccer/six-strikers-linked-with-kaizer-chiefs-are-they-good-enough/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=The Citizen |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ajira |first=Wasomi |date=2022-11-25 |title=Takwimu za Fiston Mayele Statistics So Far 2022/2023 |url=https://wasomiajira.com/takwimu-za-fiston-mayele-statistics-so-far-2022-2023/25/11/2022/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=Wasomi Ajira |language=en-US |archive-date=24 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230224172325/https://wasomiajira.com/takwimu-za-fiston-mayele-statistics-so-far-2022-2023/25/11/2022/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Philémon |date=2022-09-11 |title=Filston Mayele starts Champions League with hat-trick - Video |url=https://sportnewsafrica.com/en/breve/filston-mayele-starts-champions-league-with-hat-trick-video/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=Sport News Africa |language=en-US |archive-date=2023-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230224172320/https://sportnewsafrica.com/en/breve/filston-mayele-starts-champions-league-with-hat-trick-video/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

=== Pyramids ===
In 2023, he joined Egyptian side [[Pyramids FC|Pyramids]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2026}} On 30 August 2024, he scored the only goal in a 1–0 victory over [[ZED FC|ZED]] in the [[2024 Egypt Cup final|Egypt Cup final]], securing his club's maiden title in all competitions.<ref name="ECwin">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2024/08/30/pyramids-win-egypt-cup/ |title=Pyramids FC beat ZED in Egypt Cup final to win first-ever trophy |publisher=KingFut |date=30 August 2024 }}</ref> In the [[2025 CAF Champions League final]], Mayele made history by scoring the opening goal against [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] in the second leg of a 2–1 win, helping his team clinch their first-ever continental title with a 3–2 aggregate victory. He finished the tournament as the top scorer, netting six goals.<ref name="CAFtopscorer">{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-champions-league/news/fiston-mayele-tops-totalenergies-caf-champions-league-scorers-chart/ |title=Fiston Mayele tops TotalEnergies CAF Champions League scorers chart |publisher=CAF Online |date=1 June 2025 }}</ref>

On 23 September 2025, he netted a hat-trick for Pyramids in a 3–1 win over [[Al-Ahli Saudi FC|Al-Ahli]], securing his club's [[2025 FIFA Intercontinental Cup#African–Asian–Pacific Cup|African–Asian–Pacific Cup]] title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/intercontinentalcup/2025/articles/al-ahli-pyramids-african-asian-pacific-cup-report |title=Mayele powers Pyramids past Al Ahli |publisher=FIFA |date=23 September 2025 }}</ref> A month later, on 18 October, he scored the only goal in a 1–0 win over [[RS Berkane]] in the [[2025 CAF Super Cup|CAF Super Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.africatopsports.com/2025/10/19/mayele-the-hero-wins-caf-super-cup-for-pyramids/ |title=Mayele the hero, wins CAF Super Cup for Pyramids |publisher=africatopsports.com |date=19 October 2025 }}</ref>

== International career ==
In December 2022, Mayele was named in the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]] squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opinion-info.cd/sports/2023/12/27/liste-des-24-leopards-selectionnes-pour-la-can-cote-divoire-2023-labsence-de|title=Liste des 24 Léopards sélectionnés pour la CAN Côte d'Ivoire 2023 : l'absence de Mukoko, Lilepo et Balikwisha divise l'opinion !|publisher=Opinion Info|last=Makabi|first=Gratis|date=27 December 2023|access-date=27 December 2023|language=fr}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Mayele is the fifth son of [[Anaclet Mayele Kalala]], a former footballer who played as a goalkeeper for [[AS Bantous]] in the 1980s.<ref name=":0" /> He is nicknamed "''Monsieur le but''" (Mr. Goal) due to his goalscoring prowess.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

